summary: The video demonstrates how to create a liquid fertilizer from crushed eggshells and lemon juice. The eggshells are crushed into a fine powder and mixed with lemon juice, which causes a reaction. This mixture is then diluted in water and sprayed onto plants, or the crushed eggshells are applied directly to the soil around plants. The video states this method helps plants absorb calcium, strengthens roots, stems, leaves, and fruits, and boosts resistance to diseases and harsh weather.
transcript: Did you know that if you crush eggshells into a mortar until they become a very fine powder and then mix them with lemon juice, they immediately start reacting and forming bubbles. This happens because eggshells are alkaline and lemon juice is acidic, and it's that acid that releases the calcium trapped inside the eggshell. If you let the mixture sit for 24 hours, most of the eggshell will dissolve into the juice. Then you can dilute it in a liter of water and you'll have a liquid fertilizer rich in calcium, perfect for applying at the base of plants and also on their foliage. This homemade method allows plants to absorb calcium faster, strengthening roots, stems, leaves, and fruits. Plus, it boosts plant resistance against diseases, nutrient deficiencies, and harsh weather conditions. With this method, you recycle kitchen waste, save money, reduce trash, and increase your garden's productivity naturally, ecologically, and effectively. The best part is that it's simple, affordable, and anyone can do it at home.

This video is a quick guide to fashion history from the 1900s to the 1960s, showcasing different styles and trends for each decade. It covers the hourglass figure, defined waists, hemlines, silhouettes, and popular accessories of each era.
transcript: This is a quick guide to fashion history from the 1900s to the 1960s. First the 1900s. The 1900s. First: the 1900s. This decade had the extreme hourglass figure, large bust, and large hips. Simple white and colored blouses tucked into a long narrow skirt was the basic everyday look. The 1910s. The 1910s brought a much more natural silhouette, but the waist was definitely still defined. If you see an outfit with a ridiculous amount of lace and equally ridiculous sized hats then it's probably from the 1910s. For the 1920s, hemlines rose drastically. However, the defining factor of this decade of fashion was that there was no defined waist, as well as the iconic finger waves. 1930s. 1930s fashion was all about satin and ruffles. The silhouette was very natural and high waistlines as well. Puffy sleeves were popular. Hats were also always at a tilt. 1940s. Think of 1940s fashion as the original 1980s. Shoulder pads were in, and the overall daily look took more of a masculine approach. Women began to regularly wear pants, and long, Rita Hayworth inspired hair was popular. 1950s. Now the 1950s was the exact opposite. This decade was ultra feminine. The hourglass figure was back, and full skirts and bright colors was the staple of the decade. Hair was achieved using pin curls and was shorter than the 1940s. 1960s. Lastly, the 1960s was heavily inspired by the 1920s. This time, colors were even brighter, and skirts were even shorter. And the bigger the hair, the better. 1966. And the bigger the hair, the better.

summary: The video analyzes a soccer play where a midfielder uses feints and body positioning to evade defenders and create space. The midfielder initially pretends to head a long ball, causing a defender to drop back. The midfielder then turns and fakes a pass forward to draw pressure, before turning into the space created by the defender. Finally, a shift of bodyweight sells the move, causing the defender to lunge and allowing the midfielder to escape, leaving the defender off balance. The narrator concludes that the midfielder controls the game with his brain, not pace or power.
key_video_elements: Creator, Technology, Sports Equipment, Clothing/Fashion Items, Text/Graphics, Props
transcript: This is why Busquets is a midfield genius. A long ball comes toward him to head it. He pretends to head it. The defender behind him reads it as a header, drops back to cover space. But Busquets lets the ball drop and turns the other way. Here, the defender is pressing from behind. So Busquets fakes a pass forward to keep the pressure coming. The defender commits, lunging toward exactly what Busquets wanted. But instead of passing into the space the defender just created. He's almost caught by another defender closing in fast. But a quick shift of bodyweight sells the move. The defender lunges in, and Busquets escapes, leaving him off balance. This one is brilliant, he influences the defenders with his body positioning, then with a fake pass, he sends them all the wrong way again. Busquets never needed pace or power, he controlled the game with his brain.

Instead, I fill a soap dispenser with some fairy liquid. So we use that to wash our dishes but also to wash our hands. I only own one perfume which I wear every day and for every single occasion. The boy did not want to stay here. He walked through the forest and came to his mother's company. He saw a huge aircraft he had never seen before flying by.
